Students
INSA is a student run club and we would like to spread information about Informatics around campus while also addressing the current needs of Informatics students.  Currently, there is no website for INSA, which seems ridiculous especially because Informatics is under the school of ICS and also because there are so many brilliant Informatics students!  Students want their questions and problems to be answered.  This site must serve as a tool for current students to voice their opinions, connect with other networks and connect with students, learn current news about their major, and create a community with everything related to Informatics.
Professors
Professors want a space where they can share Informatics related material varying from current news, school-wide events, and any research opportunities that they may need assistance with.  INSA should help foster a closer relationship between the students and the professors.  Professors should be able to reach out to a community of Informatics students outside of just the classroom.  Professors have so much information that can be picked up by students.
Companies
Companies are becoming increasingly interested in the social awareness that Informatics majors have and need an outlet to communicate their company needs.  The city of Irvine is in high demand of technology driven candidates.  Having companies post job listings, retreats, internship opportunities, and whatever they see fitting geared towards students would be very helpful in developing a student’s experience.  This also allows companies related to or close to UCI to post what they are looking for.
Alumni
Alumni are vital to helping INSA stay active.  Their input is also important because we want Informatics alumni to keep in touch with the school and the major.  This relationship will allow future networking between current students and past students.  We want their advice and insight into life after graduation.  Because Informatics can be molded into a multitude of career pathways, it would be nice if students were able to see the different career possibilities with an Informatics degree.  Alumni can be very useful resources because they have gone through everything that the students have gone through.  
Teaching Assistants
Teaching Assistants are an integral part of the UC teaching structure.  Most teaching assistants are graduate students, but they differ as stakeholders because teaching assistants often have access to a lot of professors’ material that may be helpful for a class.  Teaching assistants may want to post announcements for their perspective classes or even ask undergraduate students questions for the T.A.’s research.  
Graduate Students
Graduate students can share their perspectives for students who would be interested in knowing what life is like as an Informatics graduate student.  
Prospective Students (students in high school or non-UCI students)
Prospective students will be able to understand what Informatics is all about, as well as get a peek into the student Informatics community.
INSA Board Members
A re-vamped INSA site will improve the club’s marketing, organization, and planning. INSA Board Members would want access to this site, so there must be an administrative, universal password that can be accessed by us (the webmasters) and the board.  INSA Board Members need this space as a place to inform students of upcoming INSA planned events, get feedback from students, and get students to want to get involved.
ICS Counselors
Counselors can refer students to the site as the go-to source for Informatics news and information at UCI.
Researchers
Researchers can share their work through the site, as well as potentially recruit students to assist in research.
Graduating Students
Graduating students can provide insight and feedback to fellow graduating and yet-to-graduate students about a wide variety of information such as jobs or course advice.

The lines within each task symbolizes how much we have completed of each part of the WBS.  The breaks in the lines within the progress bars represent our progress.  The spaces in those lines represent weekends because this Gantt project software does not recognize weekends as “work” (even though we did work weekends).  If that aspect of the WBS is completed, the progress bar turns green.  The parts of our website that we are still working on are represented by the yellow bars.  Notice that our implementation line within the progress bar does not fully reach the end, which means we are still working on that part of our project and have not completed the full implementation.  The lines are created by the software after inputting a percentage of how complete that component of the WBS is.  Roll out and support are the final stages of our project and will be done last; thus, they are in red because we have not begun those stages of our project.
